## Supplementary: RADAU5 Direct Convergence Analysis

The standard `solve()` interface currently cannot produce valid results for
this problem because the `ODEInterfaceDiffEq` wrapper does not forward the
Hessenberg index dimension hints required by Fortran RADAU5.  Calling
`ODEInterface.radau5` directly with `DIMOFIND1VAR=4, DIMOFIND2VAR=4,
DIMOFIND3VAR=2` on the rescaled formulation is currently the most robust
approach for this index-3 DAE.

```julia
tols = [1e-4, 1e-5, 1e-6, 1e-7, 1e-8, 1e-9, 1e-10, 1e-11, 1e-12]
errs  = Float64[]
times_wp = Float64[]
nsteps_wp = Int[]

for tol in tols
    t0 = time()
    r = solve_radau5(tol, tol)
    elapsed = time() - t0
    push!(times_wp, elapsed)
    if r.retcode == 1 && !any(isnan, r.x_end)
        push!(errs, maximum(abs.(r.x_end .- ref_final)))
        push!(nsteps_wp, r.stats["no_steps"])
    else
        push!(errs, NaN)
        push!(nsteps_wp, 0)
    end
end

println("RADAU5 Convergence (rescaled semi-explicit index-3 form):")
println("─"^70)
@printf("%-12s  %-14s  %-8s  %-10s\n", "Tolerance", "Max Error", "Steps", "Time (s)")
println("─"^70)
for i in eachindex(tols)
    @printf("%-12.0e  %-14.6e  %-8d  %-10.4f\n", tols[i], errs[i], nsteps_wp[i], times_wp[i])
end
```

```julia
plot(errs, times_wp;
     xscale=:log10, marker=:circle, legend=false,
     xlabel="Max error at t=3 vs GAMD", ylabel="Wall time (s)",
     title="RADAU5 Work-Precision (direct, index-3 rescaled form)")
```

---

## Index-3 Solver Limitations

This section documents why most solver–formulation combinations fail on this
problem.  The Car Axis index-3 structure ($\partial\phi/\partial\lambda \equiv 0$)
is the root cause.

### Standard Julia solvers on the raw mass-matrix form

```julia
println("Standard Julia solvers on the raw mass-matrix form:")
for (name, alg) in [("Rodas4", Rodas4()), ("Rodas5P", Rodas5P()),
                     ("RadauIIA5", RadauIIA5()), ("FBDF", FBDF()), ("QNDF", QNDF())]
    sol = solve(mmprob, alg; reltol=1e-5, abstol=1e-5, maxiters=Int(1e3))
    println("  ", rpad(name, 12), " → ", sol.retcode)
end
```

> All return **Unstable** because $\partial\phi/\partial\lambda \equiv 0$
> makes the Jacobian singular.  Standard implicit solvers cannot resolve the
> index-3 algebraic block.

### Why `radau()` through `solve()` produces NaN

> The `ODEInterfaceDiffEq` wrapper does not forward `DIMOFIND2VAR`/`DIMOFIND3VAR`
> to the Fortran RADAU5 solver — these options are silently dropped by the
> kwargs filter.  Without index hints, RADAU5 treats all 10 variables as index-1
> and produces NaN from step 2 onward.

### Standard solvers on the Pantelides-reduced system (MTK)

```julia
println("Standard Julia solvers on the MTK Pantelides-reduced system:")
for (name, alg) in [("Rodas5P", Rodas5P()), ("RadauIIA5", RadauIIA5()),
                     ("FBDF", FBDF()), ("QNDF", QNDF())]
    sol = solve(mtkprob, alg; reltol=1e-8, abstol=1e-8, maxiters=Int(1e3))
    println("  ", rpad(name, 12), " → ", sol.retcode)
end
```

> These return **InitialFailure** or **Unstable**.  The dummy derivative `ylˍtt`
> introduced by Pantelides takes `NaN` as its initial value; `fix_nanics` patches
> it to $-g$, but the underlying index-3 structure still prevents convergence.

### DAE solvers on the residual form

```julia
println("DAE solvers on the residual form:")
for (name, alg) in [("IDA", IDA()), ("DASSL", DASSL.dassl()), ("DASKR", DASKR.daskr())]
    try
        sol = solve(daeprob, alg; reltol=1e-5, abstol=1e-5, maxiters=Int(1e3))
        println("  ", rpad(name, 12), " → ", sol.retcode)
    catch e
        println("  ", rpad(name, 12), " → threw ", nameof(typeof(e)))
    end
end
```

> IDA, DASSL, and DASKR are index-1 DAE solvers.  They do not perform automatic
> index reduction, so this index-3 problem typically causes convergence failure.

---

## Algebraic Constraint Satisfaction

We evaluate both algebraic constraints along the direct RADAU5 trajectory:

```julia
g1_err = Float64[]
g2_err = Float64[]
for i in eachindex(radau5_ref.times)
    u = radau5_ref.states[i]
    tc = radau5_ref.times[i]
    xb = sqrt(L_ca^2 - (r_ca*sin(omega_ca*tc))^2)
    yb = r_ca*sin(omega_ca*tc)
    push!(g1_err, abs(xb*u[1] + yb*u[2]))
    push!(g2_err, abs((u[1]-u[3])^2 + (u[2]-u[4])^2 - L_ca^2))
end

plot(radau5_ref.times, [g1_err g2_err]; yscale=:log10,
     label=["|g₁| orthogonality" "|g₂| rigid axis"],
     xlabel="t", ylabel="residual",
     title="Algebraic Constraint Satisfaction (RADAU5, rtol=1e-12)")
```

---

## Summary

| Formulation | Solver | Status | Notes |
|-------------|--------|--------|-------|
| Rescaled mass-matrix + direct `ODEInterface.radau5` | RADAU5 (Fortran) | ✓ Works | Requires index hints (4,4,2) |
| Raw mass-matrix + `solve(prob, radau())` | RADAU5 via wrapper | ✗ NaN | Wrapper drops index hints |
| Raw mass-matrix + Julia solvers | Rodas/RadauIIA5/FBDF | ✗ Unstable | No index-3 support |
| MTK Pantelides-reduced | All Julia solvers | ✗ InitialFailure / Unstable | Overdetermined init |
| Residual DAE (`DAEProblem`) | IDA/DASSL/DASKR | ✗ Unstable / DomainError | Index-1 solvers, no index reduction |

Currently the most robust solver for this index-3 formulation is the Fortran
RADAU5 implementation, called directly through `ODEInterface` with the correct
Hessenberg index dimension hints and a rescaled mass matrix.

